In EKS, Kubernetes access management is mainly controlled using:

IAM (AWS Authentication)
aws-auth ConfigMap / Access Entries
RBAC (Authorization inside Kubernetes)

Complete flow looks like this:

IAM User / IAM Role
        ↓
Authentication to EKS API Server
        ↓
aws-auth ConfigMap / EKS Access Entry
        ↓
Mapped to Kubernetes User/Group
        ↓
RBAC Roles / ClusterRoles
        ↓
RoleBinding / ClusterRoleBinding
        ↓
Permissions inside cluster
1. Authentication vs Authorization

Very important concept.

Component	Purpose
IAM	Authentication
RBAC	Authorization
Authentication

Checks:

Who are you?

Handled by:

AWS IAM
aws-auth ConfigMap
EKS Access Entries
Authorization

Checks:

What are you allowed to do?

Handled by:

Role
ClusterRole
RoleBinding
ClusterRoleBinding
2. aws-auth ConfigMap (Traditional Method)

In EKS:

IAM users/roles cannot directly access Kubernetes cluster.
They must be mapped.

This mapping happens in:

kube-system/aws-auth

View:

kubectl edit configmap aws-auth -n kube-system

Example:

mapUsers: |
  - userarn: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/dev-user
    username: dev-user
    groups:
      - developers

mapRoles: |
  - rolearn: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/eks-admin-role
    username: eks-admin
    groups:
      - system:masters
3. system:masters Group

Most powerful Kubernetes group.

If mapped here:

groups:
  - system:masters

User gets:

Full cluster admin access

Equivalent to:

cluster-admin

Can:

create namespaces
delete nodes
deploy apps
modify secrets
manage RBAC
everything in cluster
4. RBAC Components
Role

Namespace-scoped permissions.

Example:

kind: Role

Can access only:

specific namespace

Example:

pod read access in dev namespace only.
ClusterRole

Cluster-wide permissions.

Example:

kind: ClusterRole

Can manage:

nodes
namespaces
cluster resources
all namespaces
RoleBinding

Attaches:

Role → User/Group/ServiceAccount

Namespace scoped.

Example:

kind: RoleBinding
ClusterRoleBinding

Attaches:

ClusterRole → User/Group/ServiceAccount

Cluster-wide.

Example:

kind: ClusterRoleBinding
5. Complete Cluster Admin Access Example
Step 1 — Map IAM user in aws-auth
mapUsers: |
  - userarn: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/rakesh
    username: rakesh
    groups:
      - eks-admins
Step 2 — Create ClusterRoleBinding
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
  name: eks-admin-binding

subjects:
- kind: Group
  name: eks-admins
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

roleRef:
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: cluster-admin
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

Apply:

kubectl apply -f clusterrolebinding.yaml
Result

That IAM user now gets:

Complete cluster-level access

Can run:

kubectl get nodes
kubectl get pods -A
kubectl delete namespace
kubectl create deployment

everything.

6. Real-Time Enterprise Access Model

Usually companies follow:

Team	Access
DevOps/Admin	cluster-admin
Developers	namespace limited
QA	read-only
CI/CD	service account limited
Monitoring tools	specific permissions
7. Modern EKS Access Entries (New Method)

AWS now recommends:

EKS Access Entries

instead of manually editing aws-auth.

Example:

aws eks create-access-entry \
  --cluster-name ecommerce \
  --principal-arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/rakesh

Then associate policy:

aws eks associate-access-policy \
  --cluster-name ecommerce \
  --principal-arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/rakesh \
  --policy-arn arn:aws:eks::aws:cluster-access-policy/AmazonEKSClusterAdminPolicy \
  --access-scope type=cluster

This gives:

cluster admin access
without editing aws-auth.
8. Full Real-Time Flow
IAM User logs in
        ↓
aws eks update-kubeconfig
        ↓
kubectl generates token using IAM
        ↓
EKS API Server validates IAM identity
        ↓
aws-auth / access entry mapping checked
        ↓
Mapped Kubernetes group identified
        ↓
RBAC policies evaluated
        ↓
Request allowed/denied
Important Commands

Check access:

kubectl auth can-i '*' '*' --all-namespaces

Check bindings:

kubectl get clusterrolebinding

Check roles:

kubectl get clusterroles

Check aws-auth:

kubectl get configmap aws-auth -n kube-system -o yaml
Most Important Interview Concept
IAM authenticates users to EKS.
RBAC authorizes actions inside Kubernetes.


