Access S3

No hardcoded keys required.

2. In EKS Pods Run Inside Nodes

Architecture:

EKS Node (EC2)
   ↓
Pods
   ↓
Containers

Initially:

Pods inherit node IAM permissions

because pod runs on node.

This creates security problem.

3. Problem Without IRSA

Suppose Node IAM Role has:

AmazonS3FullAccess

Then:

ALL pods on that node can access S3

Even malicious pod.

This violates:

Principle of Least Privilege

Huge security risk in enterprises.

4. Solution → IRSA (IAM Roles for Service Accounts)

AWS introduced:

IRSA = IAM Roles for Service Accounts

This enables:

Pod-level IAM permissions

instead of:

node-level permissions.
5. Real Flow with IRSA
Pod
 ↓
Kubernetes Service Account
 ↓
OIDC Identity Token
 ↓
AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity
 ↓
Temporary AWS Credentials
 ↓
Access S3/EBS/EFS
6. Your Understanding is Correct

You said:

Create Policy
Attach to IAM Role
Attach IAM Role to Service Account
Mention Service Account in Pod YAML

YES — exactly correct.

That is real production architecture.

7. Example Architecture
Without IRSA
Node IAM Role
   ↓
All Pods inherit permissions

Bad security.

With IRSA
Pod-A → S3 Read Only
Pod-B → DynamoDB Access
Pod-C → No AWS Access

Each pod gets isolated AWS permissions.

Enterprise-grade security.

8. Example Real-Time Flow
Step 1 — Create IAM Policy

Example:

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:GetObject"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
Step 2 — Create IAM Role

Trust relationship:

EKS OIDC Provider

allowed to assume role.

Step 3 — Create Kubernetes Service Account

Example:

apiVersion: v1
kind: ServiceAccount
metadata:
  name: s3-reader
  annotations:
    eks.amazonaws.com/role-arn: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/s3-reader-role
Step 4 — Attach Service Account in Pod
spec:
  serviceAccountName: s3-reader
Result

Only that pod can access:

S3
EFS
DynamoDB
Secrets Manager
whatever role allows.
9. Now Coming to EBS CSI Driver

Very important distinction.

EBS Access Is Different

Pods DO NOT directly call EBS APIs usually.

Instead:

Kubernetes
   ↓
CSI Driver
   ↓
AWS EBS APIs
   ↓
Volume Attach/Mount
10. EBS CSI Driver Purpose

CSI Driver manages:

create EBS volume
attach EBS to node
mount inside pod
detach/delete volumes

Automatically.

11. Real Flow for StatefulSet

Example:

mysql-0
   ↓
PVC
   ↓
StorageClass
   ↓
EBS CSI Driver
   ↓
Creates EBS volume
   ↓
Attaches to worker node
   ↓
Mounted inside container
12. Important Real-Time Concept

EBS attaches to:

NODE

NOT directly to pod.

Then kubelet mounts volume into pod container.

Flow:

EBS
 ↓
EC2 Node OS
 ↓
Container Runtime
 ↓
Pod Mount Path
13. Why EBS CSI Driver Needs IAM Permissions

Because driver itself calls AWS APIs:

CreateVolume
AttachVolume
DeleteVolume
DescribeVolumes

So:

CSI Controller Pod
needs AWS IAM permissions.

Usually via:

IRSA Service Account.
14. Real-Time Enterprise Pattern
Component	IAM Method
Application Pod	IRSA
EBS CSI Driver	IRSA
ALB Controller	IRSA
ExternalDNS	IRSA
FluentBit	IRSA

Modern EKS heavily uses IRSA.

15. Final Architecture
Application Pod
    ↓
Service Account
    ↓
IAM Role via IRSA
    ↓
Temporary STS Credentials
    ↓
AWS Services

Storage flow:

StatefulSet
   ↓
PVC
   ↓
EBS CSI Driver
   ↓
EBS Volume
   ↓
Mounted into Node
   ↓
Mounted into Pod
