This is one of the MOST important concepts in Kubernetes.

Once you deeply understand:

PV
PVC
StorageClass
CSI Driver
StatefulSet

you understand how Kubernetes manages persistent storage like real enterprise platforms.

1. Why Kubernetes Needed PV/PVC

Containers are:

Ephemeral

Meaning:

Container restart → data lost

But databases need:

permanent storage
recoverability
stable disks

So Kubernetes introduced abstraction layers.

2. Core Components

Architecture:

Pod
 ↓
PVC (Request)
 ↓
PV (Actual Disk Mapping)
 ↓
StorageClass
 ↓
CSI Driver
 ↓
Cloud Storage (EBS/EFS/etc)
3. Real-Life Analogy

Think like apartment booking.

PVC = Request Form
"I need 1GB storage"

Pod does NOT care:

where storage exists
which disk
which AWS volume

It only requests.

PV = Actual Apartment

Actual storage resource.

Example:

EBS Volume

mapped into Kubernetes object.

StorageClass = Rules/Blueprint

Defines:

gp2/gp3
SSD/HDD
encryption
reclaim policy
dynamic provisioning rules
CSI Driver = Real Provisioner

Actually talks to:

AWS
Azure
GCP
NetApp
Ceph

Creates real storage.

4. Your Current Flow (Real Example)

You created:

StatefulSet MySQL

Inside StatefulSet:

volumeClaimTemplates:

This automatically generated:

PVCs
5. Step-by-Step Internal Working
STEP 1 — StatefulSet Created

Example:

replicas: 3

Kubernetes automatically creates:

mysql-0
mysql-1
mysql-2
STEP 2 — PVC Auto Created

For each pod:

mysql-data-mysql-0
mysql-data-mysql-1
mysql-data-mysql-2

Each pod gets separate disk.

Very important for DB isolation.

STEP 3 — PVC Says

Example:

storage: 1Gi
storageClassName: ebs-storage

Meaning:

"I need 1GB EBS storage"
STEP 4 — Kubernetes Checks StorageClass

StorageClass:

provisioner: ebs.csi.aws.com

Meaning:

Use AWS EBS CSI Driver
STEP 5 — CSI Driver Triggered

CSI Controller Pod receives request.

Flow:

PVC Created
   ↓
StorageClass identified
   ↓
CSI Driver notified
STEP 6 — CSI Driver Calls AWS APIs

Using IRSA permissions:

CreateVolume API

Actual EBS volume created in AWS.

Example:

vol-0abc123
STEP 7 — PV Automatically Created

Kubernetes now creates:

PersistentVolume object

mapping:

PV ↔ Actual EBS Volume
STEP 8 — PVC Bound to PV

Now:

PVC STATUS = Bound

Meaning:

Storage request satisfied
STEP 9 — Pod Scheduling Starts

Scheduler now chooses node.

Example:

ip-192-168-13-23
STEP 10 — EBS Attached to Node

CSI Node Plugin:

AttachVolume

AWS attaches EBS disk to EC2 node.

STEP 11 — Kubelet Mounts Disk

Linux OS mounts EBS:

/dev/nvme...

Then mounted inside container path:

/var/lib/mysql
Final Result
MySQL writes data
        ↓
Container path
        ↓
Mounted EBS
        ↓
Persistent AWS storage
6. Why StatefulSet Uses Separate PVCs

Very important.

Each database pod needs isolated storage.

Example:

Pod	Volume
mysql-0	ebs-0
mysql-1	ebs-1
mysql-2	ebs-2

Otherwise:

data corruption
replication issues
filesystem locking issues
7. Important Access Modes
RWO
ReadWriteOnce

Only one node can mount.

EBS commonly uses this.

RWX
ReadWriteMany

Multiple nodes can mount.

Used with:

EFS
NFS
8. Why EBS Cannot Be Shared Across Nodes Easily

EBS is:

AZ-specific block storage

Can attach to:

one node at a time typically.

So:

excellent performance
low latency
DB workloads
9. Real Enterprise Architecture

Example:

mysql-0
   ↓
PVC
   ↓
PV
   ↓
EBS Volume
   ↓
Attached to Worker Node

Same for each replica.

10. What Happens If Pod Dies

This is KEY advantage.

Suppose:

mysql-0 pod deleted

Kubernetes recreates pod.

But PVC/PV remain.

So:

Same EBS volume remounted

Data persists.

11. Difference Between Deployment vs StatefulSet
Deployment	StatefulSet
Stateless	Stateful
Shared identity	Stable identity
Random pod names	Fixed pod names
Usually no PVC	Dedicated PVC
Good for apps	Good for DBs
12. Why CSI Driver Is Revolutionary

Before CSI:

each storage vendor custom plugins.

Now universal standard:

CSI = Container Storage Interface

Works for:

AWS EBS
Azure Disk
GCP PD
Ceph
NetApp
Portworx
